In .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides are replaced by **`Window` lifecycle events**. Override `CreateWindow` in your `App` class and use a custom `Window` subclass:

```csharp
// App.xaml.cs
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    => new MyWindow(new AppShell());

// MyWindow.cs
public class MyWindow : Window
{
    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnCreated()    { /* ≈ OnStart */  }
    protected override void OnResumed()    { /* ≈ OnResume */ }
    protected override void OnDeactivated(){ /* ≈ OnSleep */  }
    protected override void OnStopped()    { /* also OnSleep-like */ }
    protected override void OnDestroying() { /* cleanup */ }
}
```

**Key mapping:**

| Xamarin.Forms | MAUI Window |
|---|---|
| `OnStart` | `OnCreated` / `OnActivated` |
| `OnSleep` | `OnDeactivated` / `OnStopped` |
| `OnResume` | `OnResumed` |

For **platform-specific** hooks, you can also use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs` to tap into native events (e.g., `OnActivityResult` on Android).
